00:15:47.260 --> 00:15:52.710
and take elevator C to the
fifth floor suite 511."

00:15:52.710 --> 00:15:55.770
So, as you're sitting there
before your morning coffee

00:15:55.770 --> 00:16:01.570 position:56%
and you're trying to picture in your
mind what second to the left means,

00:16:01.570 --> 00:16:03.190
somebody taps you on the
shoulder and says, "Hey,

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:06.770
you know elevator C is over there."

00:16:06.770 --> 00:16:09.210
So what just happened?

00:16:09.210 --> 00:16:12.300
You were thinking very deeply
about what I said on the card

00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:17.320
and then accidentally you
broadcast your thoughts out loud

00:16:17.320 --> 00:16:20.200
and that's called subvocal speech.

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:25.770
When we think really-really hard
about something, once in a while,

00:16:25.770 --> 00:16:30.710 position:56%
there's very gentle activation of
the vocal musculature which can lead

00:16:30.710 --> 00:16:34.630
to unintended vocalization.

00:16:34.630 --> 00:16:39.610
So, subvocal speech
is very quiet mumbling

00:16:39.610 --> 00:16:43.990 position:56%
that we all do this very quiet
mumbling, but it's only been studied

00:16:43.990 --> 00:16:47.580
since you know the late 40s-50s
and it started to be studied

00:16:47.580 --> 00:16:50.350
with EMG or electromyography.

00:16:50.350 --> 00:16:52.980
Electromyography is a
technique that neurologists use

00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:57.590
that measures muscle activation
by putting a probe on muscle

00:16:57.590 --> 00:17:00.730
and it measures voltage waves.

00:17:00.730 --> 00:17:05.070
So, physiologist Lewis Gould
[assumed spelling] he took two sets

00:17:05.070 --> 00:17:07.990
of patients, half of them
with auditory hallucinations

00:17:07.990 --> 00:17:11.390
and schizophrenia and half of them
without them, control subjects.

00:17:11.390 --> 00:17:16.040
And he used EMG to measure
their vocal musculature

00:17:16.040 --> 00:17:19.100
to see what it was doing
during auditory hallucinations.

00:17:19.100 --> 00:17:20.910
And what he found is that 86%

00:17:20.910 --> 00:17:25.940
of hallucinating patients had
activation of their vocal muscles

00:17:25.940 --> 00:17:31.290
as compared to 10% of the patients
who are not having hallucinations.

00:17:34.010 --> 00:17:38.360
So Gould asked the
following question;

00:17:38.360 --> 00:17:43.420
could auditory hallucinations
be subvocal speech?

00:17:43.420 --> 00:17:49.080 position:56%
That when someone is hearing a voice
it's actually just their own very

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:53.100
quiet mumbling just somehow
getting into their heads,

00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:58.730
really-really getting to them.

00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:04.750
So then he asked another question,
he said "If that were true,

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:10.400
if auditory hallucinations are very
quiet, unintended mumbling and what

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:12.930
if he amplified that sound?

00:18:12.930 --> 00:18:14.600
What if he made it louder?

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:18.550
Could we hear the voices
in people's heads?

00:18:18.550 --> 00:18:23.270
So, in an experimental
set it looks something

00:18:23.270 --> 00:18:25.790
like what you see on
the image there.

00:18:25.790 --> 00:18:29.530
He plays sound amplifiers up
to the throats of patients

00:18:29.530 --> 00:18:34.890
who had auditory hallucinations
and then he waited by a microphone

00:18:34.890 --> 00:18:40.320 position:56%
and then when a patient had auditory
hallucination, a voice actually came

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:44.060
out of the microphone
as a soft whisper.

00:18:44.060 --> 00:18:49.020
And the whisper said, "If you're
in this mind you come out of there,

00:18:49.020 --> 00:18:51.280
but if you're not in
this mind, you won't come

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:56.360
out there, you want to stay there."

00:18:56.360 --> 00:18:59.560
"Who said that", he asks.

00:18:59.560 --> 00:19:03.190
And the patient who
name was Roy says,

00:19:03.190 --> 00:19:09.370
or she said "I said
that said the whisper.

00:19:09.370 --> 00:19:14.810
Are you talking to
yourself ", Gould asked.

00:19:14.810 --> 00:19:17.840
Roy, "No I don't" and
then he looks to himself

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:21.290
and the says, "What is it?"

00:19:21.290 --> 00:19:24.720
"Mind your own business
darling", says the whisper.

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:29.120
"I don't want him to
know what I was doing."

00:19:29.120 --> 00:19:33.270
See that recess, I spoke to
her to ask what she was doing

00:19:33.270 --> 00:19:35.630
and she said mind your business.

00:19:35.630 --> 00:19:38.560
And this is the first
time we've ever heard an

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:39.860
auditory hallucination.

00:19:39.860 --> 00:19:50.870
So, if that's true, if you believe
what these studies are getting at,

00:19:50.870 --> 00:19:56.800 position:56%
that patients with schizophrenia are
really hearing their own voice just

00:19:56.800 --> 00:20:01.400
their own sort of unattended
mumbling, then that should

00:20:01.400 --> 00:20:04.190
in itself give us a way to stop it.

00:20:04.190 --> 00:20:07.380
We can only speak one
voice at time, right?

00:20:07.380 --> 00:20:11.990
So, if the voice you're trying
to get rid of is your voice,

00:20:11.990 --> 00:20:14.570
then you should audibly
vocalize your own voice

00:20:14.570 --> 00:20:17.450
and that should prevent
the hallucination

00:20:17.450 --> 00:20:19.830
for coming if that's true, right?

00:20:19.830 --> 00:20:23.410
So they did this study
that looked at the duration

00:20:23.410 --> 00:20:28.630
of auditory hallucinations
where the intervention was one

00:20:28.630 --> 00:20:33.370
of these things keeping one's mouth
open, biting your tongue humming

00:20:33.370 --> 00:20:36.460
which is using your own
voice, making a fist

00:20:36.460 --> 00:20:38.900
or raising you eyebrows,
so when you go

00:20:38.900 --> 00:20:41.840
down on the graph that's a
reduction in the duration

00:20:41.840 --> 00:20:44.090
of the auditory hallucinations
and you can see

00:20:44.090 --> 00:20:49.310 position:56%
that humming actually improved the
duration of auditory hallucinations;

00:20:49.310 --> 00:20:57.530
decreased their length by about 60%
and this lends support of the idea

00:20:57.530 --> 00:21:02.340
that when patients are
hearing voices in their heads,

00:21:02.340 --> 00:21:08.050
the voice they hear is their own.

00:21:08.050 --> 00:21:12.560
But everybody mumbles
that's the problem,

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:16.400
everybody has this subvocal
speech, everyone in this room

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:20.090
so how come we don't hear them
as auditory hallucinations?

00:21:20.090 --> 00:21:24.140
This study tried to look at
that, again comparing patients

00:21:24.140 --> 00:21:27.850
with auditory hallucinations
and patients without them.

00:21:27.850 --> 00:21:32.560
Each person in this study
wore a headset with headphones

00:21:32.560 --> 00:21:38.060
and a speaker and everyone would
of sort of speak a passage into it

00:21:38.060 --> 00:21:40.800
and then it would be routed
back into the headphones

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:43.920
and they would basically be
listening to their own voices,

00:21:43.920 --> 00:21:49.720
but voice was first
sent into a distorter

00:21:49.720 --> 00:21:51.800
and the distorter can make
three levels of change.

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:56.330
The first being, no change so you
speak, goes back into your ear

00:21:56.330 --> 00:21:58.920
and you hear your voice
unadulterated;

00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:01.770
second scenario some distortion

00:22:01.770 --> 00:22:04.760
and the third scenario severe
distortion very-very difficult

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:10.110 position:56%
to recognize and then they
compared what the two groups thought

00:22:10.110 --> 00:22:13.230
and they could push a
button to identify what

00:22:13.230 --> 00:22:18.450
that voice sounded like; self, it's
my voice, other, a foreign voice,

00:22:18.450 --> 00:22:22.330
a hallucination or unknown
I really just can't tell.

00:22:22.330 --> 00:22:27.690
And here's what they found.

00:22:27.690 --> 00:22:32.850
So the [inaudible] the percentage
of errors so the patient with,

00:22:32.850 --> 00:22:36.520
the patients with hallucinations
clearly had far more errors

00:22:36.520 --> 00:22:40.870
in identifying the voice was their
own even with no distortion at all

00:22:40.870 --> 00:22:43.930
and far more with moderate
distortion

00:22:43.930 --> 00:22:46.990
and far-far more with
severe distortion.

00:22:46.990 --> 00:22:50.930
They could pick out what was
familiar about their own voices

00:22:50.930 --> 00:22:54.770
because their distortions kept
some of the intrinsic cadences

00:22:54.770 --> 00:22:58.980
of the voice, but there's
something about schizophrenia

00:22:58.980 --> 00:23:02.900
that they were unable to
recognize their own voices.

00:23:02.900 --> 00:23:09.510
But why? Why can't they recognize
and what's stopping them?

00:23:09.510 --> 00:23:13.400
And oddly enough, the answer
to this comes from research

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:19.670
on a very peculiar species of fish
called the mormyrid electric fish

00:23:19.670 --> 00:23:22.270
and it communicated with other fish

00:23:22.270 --> 00:23:27.550
by using electrical impulses called
EODs, or electric organ discharges

00:23:27.550 --> 00:23:32.030
and this is a cartoon showing
two fish in a courtship

00:23:32.030 --> 00:23:35.330 position:56%
that isn't working out because
there are so many different voltages

00:23:35.330 --> 00:23:38.530
and that's actually true that,
you know, certain fish respond

00:23:38.530 --> 00:23:43.100
to different types of
electrical impulses.

00:23:43.100 --> 00:23:52.960
And Curtis Bell did the following
study; he wanted to why some fish,

00:23:52.960 --> 00:23:58.170
how fish recognized their own
signals versus other signals.

00:23:58.170 --> 00:24:02.630
Because when you, when they would
fire this electrical discharge this

00:24:02.630 --> 00:24:06.830
form of communication, it's not
like a laser-directed signal

00:24:06.830 --> 00:24:10.290 position:56%
that you know pointed the fish they
wanted to talk to, it's like ripples

00:24:10.290 --> 00:24:16.070
on a pond so every receptor in
range is going to pick-up on signal

00:24:16.070 --> 00:24:19.120
that includes their own receptors.

00:24:20.630 --> 00:24:28.430
So from now on when I say, EOD,
electrical organ discharge,

00:24:28.430 --> 00:24:32.210
I want you think fishes'
voice and every time I hear,

00:24:32.210 --> 00:24:36.550
every time I say electroreceptor
or receptor I want you

00:24:36.550 --> 00:24:40.230
to think fishes' ears because
this is a form of communication

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:44.450
and this is used study
communication in human beings too.

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:47.290
So what Curtis Bell found is

00:24:47.290 --> 00:24:52.040
that the way the fish distinguished
their own signals from those

00:24:52.040 --> 00:24:56.230
of other is through something
called the command signal.

00:24:56.230 --> 00:24:58.000
And every time I say
"command signal"

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.440 position:56%
from now one you'll think intention.

00:25:00.440 --> 00:25:03.610
It's the intention to talk
just as each of us know

00:25:03.610 --> 00:25:05.300
when we're about to speak.

00:25:05.300 --> 00:25:09.180
The fish knows it's contending to
speak because it's bringing fires

00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:13.500
from something called the command
signal, the command to speak.

00:25:13.500 --> 00:25:15.200
So there you can see
the fishes' brain

00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:20.040
which you can always recognize a
fishes' brain by the tail and fins.

00:25:20.040 --> 00:25:24.300
And the fish says I want to fire
the EOD, I would like to talk

00:25:24.300 --> 00:25:27.350
to the firer command signal,
the command signal goes

00:25:27.350 --> 00:25:31.230 position:56%
to the electrical organ which is
basically the fishes' speech muscles

00:25:31.230 --> 00:25:34.220
and then I fires the EOD, it talks.

00:25:34.220 --> 00:25:39.630
So now we're going to
study the ear of the fish.

00:25:39.630 --> 00:25:43.260
So the next few slides are just
on the electroreceptor itself.

00:25:43.260 --> 00:25:46.200
This is what the receptor sees.

00:25:46.200 --> 00:25:48.970 position:56%
Whenever the receptor hears a signal

00:25:48.970 --> 00:25:53.970
from another fish you see
a big spike of voltage

00:25:53.970 --> 00:25:57.730
on this probe that Bell used.

00:25:57.730 --> 00:26:00.260
So he tried this long experiment.

00:26:00.260 --> 00:26:04.110
He took his own zapper and
the zapped an electroreceptor,

00:26:04.110 --> 00:26:07.160
he sent his own mating
call to the fish and low

00:26:07.160 --> 00:26:14.790 position:56%
and behold it detected the stimulus
and he said, "A, the fish hears me."

00:26:14.790 --> 00:26:18.410
Then he put more electrodes
on the fish's brain

00:26:18.410 --> 00:26:20.740
and he identified the
command signal.

00:26:20.740 --> 00:26:25.810
He found exactly when the fish
was intending to speak itself

00:26:25.810 --> 00:26:32.110
and then 4 milliseconds or within
4 milliseconds after that intent

00:26:32.110 --> 00:26:37.500
to speak, he fired an electro
impulse at the fish's ears,

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:43.230
at the receptor and this time, the
receptors detected nothing as if

00:26:43.230 --> 00:26:51.280
to say, the fish intended to speak
and then heard but ignored it.

00:26:51.280 --> 00:26:55.530
So for some reason the fish a
mechanism built into its circuitry,

00:26:55.530 --> 00:27:01.160
into its brain and whenever it
hears a signal within milliseconds

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:05.630
of intending to send
that signal it ignores it

00:27:05.630 --> 00:27:08.240
as if to say, I said that.

00:27:08.240 --> 00:27:13.330
I'm not going to make
a big deal about it.

00:27:13.330 --> 00:27:16.700
So, how does it dampen that signal?

00:27:16.700 --> 00:27:20.860
How does it sort of nullify
the effect on its receptor?

00:27:20.860 --> 00:27:23.360
It's not that, it has to
do with sort of the physics

00:27:23.360 --> 00:27:25.860
of the electrical signals.

00:27:25.860 --> 00:27:29.550
The represents a sort of a
positive wave, this is it's hearing

00:27:29.550 --> 00:27:34.010
in electrical form of
communication from another fish,

00:27:34.010 --> 00:27:37.000
but if the fish intended to speak

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:43.010
and that 4 millisecond window was
respected, a second signal is sent

00:27:43.010 --> 00:27:45.730
to nullify the first because
it is in the opposite direction

00:27:45.730 --> 00:27:47.660
and they cancel each other out

00:27:47.660 --> 00:27:50.180
and this has been demonstrated
in the literature.

00:27:50.180 --> 00:27:52.610
So that's the system.

00:27:52.610 --> 00:27:57.550 position:56%
Electric fish distinguish their own
speech, their own electrical firings

00:27:57.550 --> 00:28:03.640
from those of others by having
a prediction of what it's going

00:28:03.640 --> 00:28:09.300
to sound like, the negative one
and if it matches the positive one,

00:28:09.300 --> 00:28:15.750
and they cancel out and the fish
concludes that was me speaking.

00:28:15.750 --> 00:28:19.500
So that nullification
signal, that prediction

00:28:19.500 --> 00:28:22.650
of what the signal is
going to feel like is known

00:28:22.650 --> 00:28:26.690
in the animal literature as the
corollary discharge which is a sort

00:28:26.690 --> 00:28:28.590
of a confusing concept, but
I'm going to summarize it

00:28:28.590 --> 00:28:33.290 position:56%
for you this way; it's the predicted
sensory result of a motor act.

00:28:33.290 --> 00:28:40.010 position:56%
For example, if I want to raise my
arm my brain predicts how my sensory

00:28:40.010 --> 00:28:45.220
system is going to feel when
I do that and so when I do it,

00:28:45.220 --> 00:28:50.430
the actual sensation feels
like the predicted experience

00:28:50.430 --> 00:28:53.370
and because they match, the
brain draws the conclusion

00:28:53.370 --> 00:28:57.680
that I myself initiated
the act and so I don't feel

00:28:57.680 --> 00:28:58.980
like someone else moved it.

00:28:58.980 --> 00:29:01.230
I feel like I moved it.

00:29:01.230 --> 00:29:06.660
So it's the system for matching
experience to expectations.

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:08.900
It's been found in a lot
of different animals.

00:29:08.900 --> 00:29:12.710
For example, songbirds use it
to distinguish their own songs

00:29:12.710 --> 00:29:14.550
from those of other birds.

00:29:14.550 --> 00:29:18.440
Crickets use it to distinguish
their chirps from other chirps

00:29:18.440 --> 00:29:23.900
and this is sort of how we
think the whole system works,

00:29:23.900 --> 00:29:26.900
so it starts from the brain.

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:28.880
The brain sends the command signal,

00:29:28.880 --> 00:29:31.580
the intention to fire,
the intention to speak.

00:29:31.580 --> 00:29:35.300
Simultaneously it alerts the
sensory system, I'm about to fire.

00:29:35.300 --> 00:29:37.710
I'm intending to talk.

00:29:37.710 --> 00:29:39.680 position:56%
This is what it's going to feel like

00:29:39.680 --> 00:29:42.560
and that feeling is called
the corollary discharge.

00:29:42.560 --> 00:29:46.970
So then, the fish fires,
the prediction goes out

00:29:46.970 --> 00:29:49.000
and then they go to comparator.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.810
This comparator function decides,

00:29:51.810 --> 00:29:57.420
is the predicted experience
the same as the actual?

00:29:57.420 --> 00:29:58.920
If so they're a match.

00:29:58.920 --> 00:30:03.530 position:56%
If they match, it dampens the signal
and the nervous system relaxes

00:30:03.530 --> 00:30:06.350
that it's a self-generated signal.

00:30:06.350 --> 00:30:10.900
If they don't match, then the
fish concludes that signal

00:30:10.900 --> 00:30:14.220
that I intended to fire does not
match the one that I'm hearing

00:30:14.220 --> 00:30:17.540
so the one that I'm hearing
must be someone else's signal.

00:30:17.540 --> 00:30:23.980
And the same thing is thought
to happen in schizophrenia

00:30:23.980 --> 00:30:26.510
and basically in all speech.

00:30:26.510 --> 00:30:32.090
So in our brain we have a motor
command to speak that goes

00:30:32.090 --> 00:30:36.330
to the muscles of speech and at the
same time, there is a prediction

00:30:36.330 --> 00:30:38.480
of what the voice is
going to sound like.

00:30:38.480 --> 00:30:42.620
And then at the same
moment we hear our voice

00:30:42.620 --> 00:30:46.920
and then the brain compares,
there's a sound of my voice,

00:30:46.920 --> 00:30:50.830
does the sound I just heard
match the way my voice usually

00:30:50.830 --> 00:30:52.290
sounds like?

00:30:52.290 --> 00:30:55.980
If not, it's not my voice.

00:30:55.980 --> 00:30:58.260
If so, it is.

00:30:58.260 --> 00:31:01.350
Now, what if there were a
problem with comparison function?

00:31:01.350 --> 00:31:07.170 position:56%
What if every time you heard your
own voice the brain incorrectly gave

00:31:07.170 --> 00:31:13.940
you the mismatch signal and you
weren't able to recognize it?

00:31:16.130 --> 00:31:18.020
You wouldn't think
it was your voice.

00:31:18.020 --> 00:31:21.090
You would think it was that of
someone else, so that's sort

00:31:21.090 --> 00:31:26.690 position:56%
of the basic premise, the basic part
of the argument as to why people

00:31:26.690 --> 00:31:31.210
with schizophrenia can't
recognize their own voice,

00:31:31.210 --> 00:31:32.880
but there's a problem.

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:35.740
If this is all about
voices then what

00:31:35.740 --> 00:31:37.810
about schizophrenia in the deaf?

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:40.950 position:56%
Do they have auditory hallucinations
even though they can't hear their

00:31:40.950 --> 00:31:42.250
own voice?

00:31:42.250 --> 00:31:47.280
And the answer is they do have
auditory hallucinations in a sense.

00:31:47.280 --> 00:31:51.350
So this is an example of a
patient who has schizophrenia

00:31:51.350 --> 00:31:55.740
and has been deaf since before
age 2, so basically as far

00:31:55.740 --> 00:32:00.140
as we can remember and this
is a little blurb about him;

00:32:00.140 --> 00:32:02.370
he says he claims to
have seen Jesus.

00:32:02.370 --> 00:32:05.500
He often hears a voice
communicating to him from London.

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:08.300
When asked how he as a deaf
person could hear someone

00:32:08.300 --> 00:32:11.910
from London he replies that
he can see the arms and hands

00:32:11.910 --> 00:32:16.160
of the purple, excuse me of
the person signing to him,

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:19.660
so auditory hallucinations
in the deaf consist

00:32:19.660 --> 00:32:22.940
of hallucinating sign language.

00:32:22.940 --> 00:32:26.900
Now this poses a problem
for the theory, right?

00:32:26.900 --> 00:32:31.540
If auditory hallucinations
are all misinterpretations

00:32:31.540 --> 00:32:36.500
or the brain misjudging
their own voices,

00:32:36.500 --> 00:32:40.380
not recognizing your own
voices, then what explains this?

00:32:40.380 --> 00:32:43.290
So we have to extend
the theory it's not

00:32:43.290 --> 00:32:45.800
that patients can't
